description: From Middle French structure, from Latin structūra (“a fitting together, adjustment, building, erection, a building, edifice, structure”), from struere, past participle structus (“pile up, arrange, assemble, build”). Compare construct, instruct, destroy, etc.

entries.meaning: A cohesive whole built up of distinct parts.
The underlying shape of a solid.
examples: He studied the structure of her face.

entries.meaning: The overall form or organization of something.
examples: Synonyms: makeup, configuration; see also Thesaurus:composition

entries.meaning: A set of rules defining behaviour.
examples: For some, the structure of school life was oppressive.

entries.meaning: (computing) Several pieces of data treated as a unit.
examples: This structure contains both date and timezone information.

entries.meaning: (fishing, uncountable) Underwater terrain or objects (such as a dead tree or a submerged car) that tend to attract fish
examples: There's lots of structure to be fished along the west shore of the lake; the impoundment submerged a town there when it was built.

entries.meaning: A body, such as a political party, with a cohesive purpose or outlook.
examples: The South African leader went off to consult with the structures.

entries.meaning: (logic) A set along with a collection of finitary functions and relations.

verbs.description: structure (third-person singular simple present structures, present participle structuring, simple past and past participle structured)

entries.meaning: (transitive) To give structure to; to arrange.
examples: I'm trying to structure my time better so I'm not always late.
I've structured the deal to limit the amount of money we can lose.
